message: Officially a Member of the #115thCongress. I am excited to get to work for the Hoosiers of #IN09!
Thanks to all those from #IN09 who reached out regarding this issue. It is my strongest belief that the House should always be transparent.
I am honored that my colleagues have selected me to serve on the House Financial Services Committee. Together, we will reduce the burden of federal regulations!
In case you missed it yesterday, I gave my inaugural floor speech in support of the #REINSAct which the House passed last night.

Congratulations to President-elect Donald Trump and Vice President-elect Mike Pence on being certified as the next President and Vice President of the United States by a Joint Session of Congress today.

Today, I had the distinct honor and privilege of presenting a U.S. Flag, flown over the Capitol, to the #GoldStarFamily of SGT. Matthew L. Deckard, of Floyds Knobs, IN, in honor of his ultimate sacrifice. I am so glad I was able to join the Deckard family for this Honor and Remember - Indiana Chapter presentation.

Today is #LawEnforcementAppreciationDay and we should take a moment to thank those who protect and serve our communities throughout #IN09. I am currently making calls to Sheriffs and Police Chiefs across the District thanking them for the service that their departments perform on our behalf.

Early this afternoon, I introduced my first piece of legislation: a Constitutional Amendment in favor of #TermLimits for Members of Congress. I made a promise to my fellow Hoosiers: that my highest priority in Congress will be working to return our government to one that is by the people and for the people. I am upholding my commitment to lead the fight for #TermLimits to ensure that Members of Congress serve constituents as public servants. As all Hoosiers know, our actions speak louder than our words. That is why I made sure that my first official act was to draft this important piece of legislation that Hoosiers desperately wish to see enacted.

Since day one, Obamacare has failed the American people: health insurance options have been greatly reduced, premiums have skyrocketed, and the government-created co-ops have already lost taxpayers over $1 billion. Obamacare is bad for American families' health care and has dampened job creation.  Now is the time for #FullRepeal.
A quick #TBT to the article from the Indiana Daily Student about the first piece of legislation I introduced: #TermLimits!

Today, under Obamacare, the average American family premiums have soared by $4,300 and now totals a little less than $20,000 annually. Remember when President Obama promised premiums would decline by $2,500 per family under Obamacare? Obviously it is time for #FullRepeal and a #BetterWay.

Today, we took the first step towards #FullRepeal by voting to defund Obamacare. Not only has this legislation been unaffordable, but it has also been devastating to small businesses and American families. Obamacare’s legacy will be one where 18 of the 23 exchanges that were set up by the government to benefit consumers failed. A health care option should not have premiums that increase by double digits all while choices for those who depend on this system decrease. Hoosiers and all Americans deserve a #BetterWay for health care: one where free market choices compete for Hoosiers’ hard-earned dollars.

On Sundays, my family and extended family gathers to complete an afternoon of community service together. Today, we spent time at a local food kitchen. It is extremely important that everyone takes time to give back to their community at all levels.

Yesterday, in remembrance of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., I had the privilege of participating in a Memorial March in Jeffersonville. Dr. King's legacy is one of passionate leadership and selfless service that continues to inspire many throughout the world.

Yesterday was a busy day meeting with constituents and small business owners across #IN09! I started the morning meeting with Mayor Troy Merry of Salem, IN. I made sure to stop in and speak with Rita at Lincks Clothing and Shoes before meeting with Washington County Assessor Jason Cockerill.   From there, I made a stop at the Salem Apothecary and spoke with Rebecca about overreaching government regulations that force her to change the way she has been doing business for decades.   After a quick lunch at Christie's On The Square, I made the trip to Mitchell, IN to meet with Mayor JD England.   Next, I spent some time talking with the team at Springer-Springer Insurance in Orleans, IN about how their business is doing in today's economic climate.   Afterwards, I met with the team at Ramsey Popcorn Company and heard about all the great products they produce right here in Harrison County.   I ended the day with the Town of Clarksville honoring two Officers with the Clarksville Police Department who had been named Officers of the Year.   It was a packed day, but we're just getting started. I look forward to cross-crossing #IN09 multiple times in the coming months.
Not very long from now, America will have its 45th President inaugurated. I look forward to working with President Donald J. Trump and Vice President Mike Pence! #IN09
It was a pleasure to welcome Hoosiers from across #IN09 to THEIR office in Washington, D.C. for this momentous occasion.
Glad to see that President Donald J. Trump took the first steps to ensuring that unaccountable government bureaucrats stop leveling burdensome regulations on hardworking Hoosiers.

I am proud to announce that the new, personalized website for #IN09 has been launched! This site contains all of the contact information for offices both in District and in Washington, D.C. as well as some helpful information about dealing with the federal government.
These men embodied the principles that mankind has embraced for centuries. We are meant to be explorers. We are meant to ask questions, dive deeper, reach farther, and fly higher. #Apollo1

On this day in history (January 31, 1871 to be exact), the land was purchased to build Quartermaster Station in Jeffersonville, IN. I am proud to continue the tradition of maintaining a District Office in this historic place. Learn more about the intriguing history of the quadrangle and how it became a necessary military depot after the Civil War.

The Supreme Court of the United States was always envisioned to be the democratic conscience of our government. We the people need to return the Supreme Court to the role our Founding Fathers envisioned: one where the Court determines the constitutionality of issues, not legislates from behind the bench. This next #SCOTUS can return this institution to its rightful high perch in our beautiful Republic.

The Obama Administration developed a rule that, due to their lack of business experience, lessened the options small investors had available to enhance their retirements. Today, President Donald J. Trump returned options to millions of Hoosier and American investors by signing an Executive Order that struck down this misguided rule.

Yesterday, the House unanimously passed H.Res. 387 which updated the Electronic Communications Privacy Act. Notably, it requires law enforcement to obtain a warrant for emails and clarifies privacy requirements for cloud computing services.

I was honored to sit down with Indiana Bankers Association to talk about how we need to get intrusive, big government out of the way and empower lenders to enable more robust opportunities for Hoosiers.

I had an absolutely wonderful time visiting the Hoosier Uplands Head Start and Early Head Start program in Bedford. It was amazing to see the impact that teachers and the entire team at Hoosier Uplands have on children and families within Lawrence County. Thank you so much for inviting me to spend time with all of you.

Today, Chairwoman Janet Yellen testified before the House Committee on Financial Services. It is imperative that we drive changes to the Fed that are necessary for the future growth and success of the American Economy.

This editorial from Investor’s Business Journal perfectly sums up economic freedom under the Obama Administration: “…the U.S. [Freedom] Index was dragged down by Obama’s anti-growth war on businesses, investors, and other productive elements of the economy.” The time to restore American #EconomicFreedom is now.
Congratulations to the Eastern High School Lady Musketeers of Pekin on winning the Indiana Girl's Basketball 2A State Championship this afternoon!

Before my District work week could begin, I had the privilege of presiding over the House of Representatives Thursday evening prior to grabbing my flight home. We hit the ground running Friday morning by joining AT&T in New Albany for the announcement that new Fiber internet is coming to Southern Indiana. From there, I went and toured a Home Depot and discussed how important it is to their business that their employees remain thoughtful, knowledgeable, and approachable to keep customers first. Next, I had the opportunity to join the White River Township Fire Department at their annual awards dinner where we recognized the Firefighter, EMT, Paramedic, Officer, and Employee of the Year.  The next work day took us to Bloomington where I had the chance to tour Baxter Pharmaceuticals and meet with so many people that help save lives daily (they told me that every second, one of their products is administered somewhere in the world)! We ran up the road a little ways and visited with Bybee Stone Co, Inc where we talked about how stone from the Hoosier State makes its way all across the globe for projects. Before calling it a day, I sat down with educators from the Cook Center for Entrepreneurship at Ivy Tech Community College where we discussed the challenges facing students and teachers.   The next day, I spent time in Bedford where I met with local pharmacists and discussed how some excessive government regulations have made necessary prescriptions too expensive for Hoosiers. I also had a chance to tour Best Home Furnishings and see some great AMERICAN craftsmen in action.   The following two days, I had an opportunity to meet with members of the Greater Greenwood Chamber of Commerce as well as One Southern Indiana Chamber & Economic Development where I took questions on a whole range of issues that impact businesses of all sizes including an overburdensome federal government and a mandated healthcare program that doesn't work for employers, employees, or providers.  Additionally, I had productive conversations with local elected officials where we discussed issues that are impacting Hoosiers on the most local level and what can be done to address them. I also had a chance to visit Central Nine Career Center where I saw firsthand how they provide robust, hands-on training to those students who are passionate about joining the Hoosier workforce.   Finally, the team at Caterpillar invited me to tour their facility and experience how they re-manufacture engines, empower their workforce by fostering a community, and see how their "cobots" help human workers complete tasks. I also had a great opportunity to speak with the Keeping Our Public Politically Informed (KOPPI) student group at Center Grove High School. These young minds are the future of not only our state but our nation and they asked some great questions about our government and how they can remain involved and informed.  On top of all of these visits throughout our community, I also continued my daily habit of calling at least 50 random constituents a day to hear directly from them how they feel their government is working as well as what issues are important to their families.   I continue to value every minute I get to spend at home speaking with fellow Hoosiers. That's why I am on the first possible flight home from Washington, D.C. and on the last possible flight back. I am honored to represent you in the House of Representatives.

Our Caseworker, Shelly, is a graduate of Eastern High School in Pekin and was a Lady Musketeer herself. So, in celebration of the Lady Musketeers winning the State Championship on Saturday, some co-workers decorated her office. Congratulations again Eastern High School Lady Musketeers!
Yesterday, I had the opportunity to sit down with Erin McPike and the team at Independent Journal Review. I enjoyed the conversation and appreciate the invitation to join them.

A quick #TBT and a big thank you to the students at the Hoosier Uplands Head Start and Early Head Start for providing some beautiful artwork that is proudly hanging in the Jeffersonville office of Indiana's 9th District!

Yesterday, I had the opportunity to recognize Clark County Indiana Sheriff's Office Deputy Wes Harper's life-saving actions on the Floor of the United States House of Representatives. Thank you Deputy Harper for your faithful dedication and unwavering devotion to Hoosiers.

For any constituents that are graduates of Franklin Community Schools in Johnson County: The school district is accepting nominations for its 2017 Hall of Fame Class. Nomination forms can be found at the link below. Tomorrow is the deadline!

Yesterday, I met with corn and soybean farmers from Southern Indiana. Like many small business owners, they have contended with overbearing bureaucrats and excessive regulations for too long. I look forward to working with them to make sure government does not prevent or deter those who grow the crops that end up on our dinner tables or in our gas tanks.
As I do every day, I spent time this morning calling random constituents across #IN09 to discuss issues that are important to them and their families.

Indiana is leading the way in medical device and bio-tech innovation. That is why I am proud to have introduced the Fostering Innovation Act with Congresswoman Kyrsten Sinema yesterday. This bipartisan, commonsense reduction of burdensome regulations will empower many industries throughout the Hoosier state to devote more resources to product innovation, research, and development. Read more about this legislation here: http://hollingsworth.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=48
My statement about the health care legislation:

It’s official! Last week, President Trump gave the Keystone XL Pipeline the necessary authorization to move forward. This project will create good-paying American jobs and ensure America’s energy independence which increases our national security.

The Consumer Financial Protection Bureau (CFPB) has failed in its core mission and has become a partisan seat of tyranny focused on suffocating small businesses and shackling consumers with bad policy.
Attention high school students across Indiana's 9th District: be on the lookout for information about the 2017 Congressional Art Competition!

I wanted to take a few minutes during #TelecommunicationsWeek to thank all 911 Dispatchers, especially those in the 9th District, for working tirelessly to keep our Police, Fire, and EMS professionals safe. While they might sometimes go unrecognized, there is no doubt that 911 Dispatchers represent the front lines of First Responders.
Today is President Thomas Jefferson's birthday. As a founding father and author of our Declaration of Independence, our nation can credit its creation to this patriot.
From our family to yours, Happy Easter.

The April District Work Period is still underway, but it has already been extremely productive! It started nearly two weeks ago by visiting the Greenwood Municipal Airport where we discussed how they continue to grow and what that means for how the FAA categorizes them. Following that, I participated in a legislative townhall in Brownstown with representatives from state and local governments that was hosted by the Brownstown Chamber of Commerce. I also had the opportunity to visit with local businesses in Clark County to see how they continue to find innovative ways to serve the community. Last week, I was fortunate to be invited to address the attendees of a national security symposium at the Naval Surface Warfare Center, Crane Division; a military installation here in Indiana that is of extreme importance. Afterwards, I met with representatives with Citizens' Climate Lobby Indiana in Bloomington. I also had the chance to tour Seven Oaks Classical School where I saw students of all ages actively engaged in their learning process. I even had a chance to read a book to some kindergarteners. We ended that day in Bloomington by holding a Veterans Roundtable where we discussed critical issues facing those individuals who bravely and honorably defending our nation.  Stay on the look out for part 2 of the April District Work Period!

Attention all high school students: the deadline to submit your artwork for the 2017 Congressional Art Competition is this week! Make sure your talents are showcased! More information can be found here:

Today, I voted against a Continuing Resolution measure that promoted the very culture and status quo that I was sent to Washington, D.C. to combat. The resolution that was presented would fund the federal government for an additional week at current spending levels for out-of-date priorities. Traditionally, Continuing Resolutions are passed in lieu of in-depth and comprehensive budgets. Instead of listening to the chorus of American voices demanding real change, politicians kicked the can down the road and promoted 'politics as usual.' I did not vote to continue funding Obamacare; I did not vote to continue out-of-control spending; I did not vote to continue inadequately-resourcing our men and women in uniform. Today, I voted to change the culture in Washington, D.C.
This past Saturday, the United States Navy christened the newest Virginia-class submarine, the Indiana. This submarine is the 4th vessel to be named for the great Hoosier state.

These pieces of artwork were submitted for consideration for the 2017 Congressional Art Competition by high school students from across Indiana's 9th District. The Grand Prize submission will be displayed in the U.S. Capitol Building for the next year. You can help us select the winners by voting for your favorite pieces with a "Like." Part of the scoring rubric reflects how many "Likes" the student's submission received on Facebook.  PLEASE be respectful of the time and energy that these young artists dedicated to each piece of artwork. Because the focus of this competition is the art, any and all comments left on this album will be deleted.
Small businesses are responsible for creating 63% of new jobs in the United States! #SmallBusinessWeek
Today, I voted against the $1.1 trillion spending bill because it neglected critical priorities such as our nation's nearly $20 trillion debt.

I released the following statement after casting a 'yea' vote for the American Health Care Act.  "The American people have lived with the burden of broken promises that Obamacare has left in its wake: higher premiums than promised, fewer choices than promised, and less access than promised. The passage of the American Health Care Act brings relief as that burden is lifted and Obamacare begins to unravel and fall away. The American Health Care Act is built upon the foundation of conservative principles, such as free-market solutions, returning power to the states, and protecting those Americans with pre-existing conditions. Today, the American people's goal of repealing Obamacare took physical form."

Don't forget to vote for your favorite submission with a "LIKE". All submissions were created by high school students across #IN09.  PLEASE be respectful of the time and energy that these young artists dedicated to each piece of artwork. Because the focus of this competition is the art, any and all comments left on this album will be deleted.

Over 40 pieces of artwork were submitted by #IN09 District high school students for consideration in the 2017 Congressional Art Competition. I am excited to announce that the Grand Prize winner is Ms. Jenna Townsend for her piece "A Look Into My Life." I would also like to recognize Ms. Kelsey Humphrey, Mr. Gavin Livingston, and Ms. Shantanna Argueta. Many thanks to all the talented students who submitted their artwork.
This week, we celebrate nurses across #IN09 and the country who sacrifice time with their families in order to care for their patients. Thank you.
Happy Mother's Day to mothers across #IN09.
During #NationalPoliceWeek, we give thanks for all those who keep our communities safe.

This past weekend, the community of Salem was devastated by flooding. Businesses, schools, and infrastructure were severely damaged. Prior to visiting the city, I spoke with Mayor Troy Merry by phone where I asked him what resources your Congressional office could help provide. Both on the phone and during my visit, it was abundantly clear that city officials and the residents of Salem had come together as a community to overcome this unexpected travesty and immediately started working to restore normalcy to the city they call home.

Last week, as #NationalPoliceWeek came to a close, I introduced legislation that aims to protect law enforcement officers from becoming vulnerable targets and potential victims. The POLICE Act helps keep the men and women who protect our communities safe. At the end of the day, the trust we place in law enforcement officers does not end at the door frame of a federal building and neither should our laws. http://hollingsworth.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=77

As we enjoy this Memorial Day, it is important that we pause, reflect, and give thanks for all those brave men and women who have faithfully and courageously paid the ultimate price for this great nation. Furthermore, let us use this time to reaffirm our resolve, in light of recent events, that freedom around the world should be protected and defended in the face of all evil.

In case you missed it, I wrote a guest column regarding my "Nay"  vote for the Continuing Resolution that Congress considered. At the end of the day, I simply could not support a measure that failed to prioritize issues that are important to Hoosiers such as our national debt, appropriate resourcing for our military, protecting our borders, investing in infrastructure, and keeping our promises to seniors. (If you don't subscribe to the The Reporter-Times, you can read the column on my website: https://hollingsworth.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=81)

The time has come for Congress to pass term limits legislation on itself so that we can return to the style of government our founders envisioned - one where citizens would go and serve their nation for a short time and then return to private life. That is why I have written and introduced term limit legislation as well as added my name to seven additional term limits bills because this issue is vitally important to the future of our republic. This is not an issue or cause where it is important that one person get credit. Instead, we must come together as a team to pass this commonsense reform supported by so many Americans.

Hours before the D-Day landings, General Eisenhower issued an order telling the soldiers, sailors, and airmen of the Allied Expeditionary Force that the eyes of the world were upon them and that they had the hopes and prayers of liberty-loving people everywhere. 73 years later, on this anniversary of D-Day, the liberty-loving people of the world have not forgotten the bravery and the sacrifices made in defense of freedom.

A quick #TBT to when the House of Representatives utilized the Congressional Review Act earlier this year to overturn 14 overreaching federal regulations that saved Americans $3.7 billion in regulatory costs and 4.2 million hours that can now be spent with family or growing and expanding businesses.

This afternoon, the House passed the Financial CHOICE Act. This commonsense legislation returns power to consumers, brings overzealous regulations into check, and sends the era of "too big to fail" to the pages of history where it belongs. The CHOICE Act is the starting gun that will get our economy off and running.
In case you missed it, the Indiana Daily Student - idsnews wrote an article about some recent legislation I introduced.

Please join me in keeping Majority Whip Congressman Steve Scalise, members of the U.S. Capitol Police, and everyone else who was targeted by this horrific shooting this morning in your thoughts and prayers.

This is the kind of government waste and inefficiencies that exist when you allow unelected bureaucrats to set our nation’s priorities. I applaud President Donald J. Trump for putting a stop to this unnecessary use of taxpayer dollars and pledge to work with him to continue slashing the bloated government bureaucracy.

I just released the following statement regarding President Donald J. Trump's decision to repeal the Environmental Protection Agency's Waters of the United States rule.  "The ill-conceived Waters of the United States rule was a crushing, overreaching regulation that would have prevented Hoosier farmers from providing for their families and created uncertainty for economic development throughout rural America. I have consistently heard from 9th District farmers that this onerous regulation would have brought about nothing but obstruction for middle-class farm families. Thanks to President Trump's decision, Hoosier farmers and the American people scored a major victory over Washington, D.C. bureaucrats."

Today, I had the distinct honor and privilege of welcoming Ms. Jenna Townsend, and her parents, to Washington, D.C. for the unveiling of her artwork in the United States Capitol. As you might remember, Jenna is the Grand Prize winner of the #IN09 2017 Congressional Art Competition and visitors to the U.S. Capitol will get to experience her art for the next year!

This evening, the House of Representatives passed two bills that reinforce the promise that was made to the American people that public safety is a top priority. The No Sanctuary for Criminals Act and #KatesLaw ensure that our nation's immigration laws are properly enforced and helps prevent illegal aliens that come to this country and commit felony crimes from becoming repeat offenders that endanger our communities.

"...And for the support of this Declaration, with a firm reliance on the protection of Divine Providence, we mutually pledge to each other our Lives, our Fortunes, and our sacred Honor." — The Declaration of Independence, 1776. Happy 4th of July!

Planned Parenthood claims that abortion services make up less than 5% of their operations. Yet, this federally subsidized organization was responsible for 73% of all abortions in the Hoosier State last year. Even more shocking: Abortions increased almost 24% in Bloomington alone in 2016. The time to defund Planned Parenthood is now! Life is sacred no matter what stage. I am proud to remain steadfast in my commitment to life and will continue fighting for those who cannot fight for themselves.

Attention Johnson County Residents:  There are currently areas of flooding in the Franklin, IN area and the chance for more rain is in the forecast. The City of Franklin Police Department has established the Franklin Middle School as a safe location for residents who may be evacuated or otherwise do not feel safe at their current location due to rising waters. This emergency shelter is available for all Johnson County residents.  Those seeking shelter at the middle school, 625 Grizzly Cub Drive (pool entrance on the south side of the building), should contact the City of Franklin Police Department at 317-736-3670 for further instructions. If you need immediate assistance or emergency help is needed, contact Johnson County Dispatch at 317-346-6336.

A #TBT to last week's District Work Week. It was great to spend time in the northern part of the District meeting with representatives from the medical field as well as the administration at Franklin College. I also spent time back in The City of Salem checking in with local businesses and residents to see how they were doing after the recent flooding they experienced. I was also privileged to be invited by Coach Cooley to speak to the New Albany High School football team before one of their summer practices prior to a visit to Squire Boone. I also was able to meet with operators of the L&I Railroad that runs the length of #IN09.

This past Friday, I proudly voted in favor of the 2018 National Defense Authorization Act (NDAA) because it prioritizes the rebuilding of our military, the proper resourcing of our warfighters, and a long overdue increase in pay that our military families need and deserve.

Last evening, I spent several hours making random phone calls to constituents across #IN09. These calls are the highlight of my day when I am in Washington because they ensure that I am hearing the voices of the Hoosiers who have entrusted me to represent them.

I was happy to play a role in the effort to #BringBeckhamHome. I was reminded how Hoosiers are fighters, and Baby Beckham is no exception. I am honored to fight for Hoosiers in Washington, in getting back from Mexico, and wherever the fight may be!
As a businessman, I know we need better-paying jobs and, though unemployment is low in Indiana, too many Hoosiers still feel like their American dream is out of reach.
The fight to slash a bloated federal government is off to a great start! For every new regulation, Congress and the President have cut sixteen existing regulations.

Hoosiers wanted security — North Korea is inching closer to nuclear capability and terrorism in Europe threatens to spread to America — meanwhile, congressional Democrats are engaged in petty partisan politics. Two days ago, Democrats put partisanship above Americans' safety and voted down two bills they had previously supported. The VA Bonus Transparency Act passed the Senate by Unanimous Consent and the Intelligence Authorization Act passed the House Intelligence Committee unanimously, but given the opportunity to obstruct, congressional Democrats just couldn't help themselves. Hoosiers deserve leaders who represent their priorities, not object to them.

Earlier this week, the House Committee on Financial Services unanimously passed my bipartisan legislation that I wrote with Congresswoman Kyrsten Sinema. This legislation makes it easier for companies to raise capital faster to grow, hire, and invest in America.

Earlier this week, I had the distinct honor and privilege to present Mr. Jim Farr the American Campaign Medal, the World War II Victory Medal, the Honorable Discharge Button, and the Honorable Service Lapel Pin. Mr. Farr never received these items prior to his Honorable Discharge from the United States Navy. I enjoyed hearing his story and am thankful for his service to our great nation.

This past week has been busy and productive across #IN09.  I enjoyed welcoming a new business to Clark County and meeting with representatives from Wesbanco - we brainstormed ways to assist small business owners so they can create more jobs for Hoosiers. I was also able to tour Fuji Seal and the Autoneum where we discussed how they are manufacturing products that are used daily across the world. Additionally, the team at Enjoy Life showed me the process that has helped them become an international leader in allergy-friendly food brand.  While in Bloomington, I had the opportunity to sit down with representatives from sheriff's offices from across the district to discuss concerns they face on a daily basis. I also toured Oliver Winery and heard from local Realtors about federal policy issues that impact them. A great conversation with the leadership team at Wheeler Mission Ministries about the service they provide to Monroe County followed.  Every single day, I am honored to represent the best constituents of any Member of Congress. Hoosiers across #IN09 are the most innovative and impressive in the state of Indiana. Thank you for allowing me to serve you in the House of Representatives.

The bigotry, hatred, and violence demonstrated in #Charlottesville today does not represent the ideals or morals of our great nation. These actions must be condemned and our prayers must remain with those who were injured or killed.

Over the course of the last 8 years, Americans have watched as their ability to make decisions about their health care have slowly been stripped from them and handed over to a bureaucratic machine. The time has come for us take back control of our health care decisions.
Take a few minutes to sign up for email updates from your congressional office!

If you received this year’s Congressional Action Survey, please send back your response by August 28th in the provided return envelope! If you didn’t receive a survey this time . . . don’t worry! We'll be sending out another one soon!

Yesterday, I had the opportunity to sit down and have a discussion about legislation that is impactful to the fire service with local firefighters, fire chiefs, and representatives from state associations. These stakeholders had reached out to me several months ago to discuss the Firefighter Cancer Registry Act. After reviewing the legislation, I was happy to tell these local heroes that I had added my name as a co-sponsor to this important bill.

Yet again, rampant bureaucracy infringes on Americans' freedoms by choosing winners and losers at the whim of bureaucrats. Without your permission, federal bureaucrats decided to close businesses of which they - not you - disapproved. That effort was stopped by your representatives.
Please join me in keeping the City of Salem's Police Chief in our thoughts and prayers as he recovers from emergency surgery.

Attention all middle school and high school students in Indiana's 9th District: I am proud to announce that I will be hosting an Academy Day on September 9th in Seymour, IN. If you're interested in learning more about the United States service academies and the process of securing a nomination, I encourage you to attend this event.
I am excited to highlight just a few of the beautiful spots in Orange County on the 9th Congressional District website:
I applaud Democrat Lee Hamilton for sharing a surefire way to have more Hoosier voices heard throughout Washington. I agree with him 100%.
The House of Representatives is working to spur economic growth by repealing Dodd-Frank and investing in Main Street rather than Wall Street.
The House of Representatives is prioritizing national security by investing in proper resources for our warfighter and providing service members with their largest pay raise in eight years.

The House of Representatives is providing peace of mind for American families by funding the fight against opioids & passing sweeping reforms to end human trafficking that include tougher penalties of traffickers and increased support for victims.

The House of Representatives is addressing dysfunction in Washington, D.C. by demanding accountability at the VA, striking harmful regulations from the books, and limiting power of bureaucrats by making major regulations subject to an up-or-down vote of Congress.

I am pleased that President Trump is reversing the Obama-era rule that denied local law enforcement access to surplus lifesaving equipment. Those who stand watch along the Thin Blue Line can now better complete their core mission of protecting our communities, particularly in the event of disasters and terror threats.

I was honored to visit Naval Surface Warfare Center, Crane Division again last week. This Center is of vital importance to the United States, Indiana, and our economy. I look forward to continuing to work with these brave patriots.

Recently, I had the honor of recognizing Sergeant Brandon White and Officer Seth Sage with the Seymour Police Department for their quick thinking and decisive action that resulted in the rescue of a one-year old from a near drowning. Their actions are a testament to the training they receive and their dedication to our community.

This afternoon in Bloomington, I had the great privilege to spend a few minutes with the brave men and women who will be ensuring the safety of everyone at #MemorialStadium for tonight's #IUvsOSU game.

Last night, I was able to join the town of Brooklyn at the dedication of a new water fountain. It was absolutely amazing to spend time with this wonderful community and speak with the excited children that were responsible for raising half of the funds of the project. There is an old saying when it comes to raising children — it takes a village. After last night, I can attest that Brooklyn has proven it takes a town.

Hoosiers want bipartisan results that improve Americans’ lives. Improving Access to Capital Act is just that; I was able to work with my Democrat colleague, Rep. Kyrsten Sinema, to provide small businesses more opportunities to grow and invest right here at home.

Today, Representatives from every corner of this great nation put aside their differences to help our fellow Americans who felt the devastation caused by Hurricane Harvey. Hoosiers know better than anyone what it means to lend a helping hand and to genuinely be concerned for our neighbors. Just as we did when our own local communities flooded recently, Hoosiers stand ready to help our fellow Americans.
9:30 pm and the work day isn't over for your Congressional office. As I wait for late votes, I am writing back to constituents who sent emails today.
Reminder for all middle school and high school students in #IN09!

On Wednesday, I voted for a clean disaster aid package because I do believe that we should help our neighbors when they need it most. However, what I voted against today was Washington, D.C.’s style of “problem-solving.” The continuing resolution and debt ceiling package created by the United States Senate is the exact opposite of what Hoosiers demanded this past November. We expect a government that plans for the future like we do here at home. Linking bad legislative tricks to disaster recovery is not only bad government, it is immoral and the American people deserve better.

Sixteen years ago, what started as a beautiful day like any other, quickly turned into a day of terror that we will never forget. On Tuesday, September 11, 2001, terrorists sought to break the spirit of the American people, but on that day and the days since, the American people have found a way to stand united — shoulder to shoulder — in the face of evil. We remember those who perished and the legacies they left behind . . . legacies of compassion, confidence, freedom, and humanity. Those who lost their lives honor us and we should do everything within our power to honor them.

Congratulations to my hometown of Jeffersonville Indiana for being selected to decorate The White House's Indiana tree this year! The 9th District has so many talented Hoosiers and I am excited to see the ornaments that some of those artists produce.

North Korea's continued pursuit of nuclear weapons threaten American interests both at home and abroad. I am proud to be an original co-sponsor of this bipartisan legislation that passed unanimously out of the House Committee on Financial Services.

North Korea poses a threat to American interests both at home and abroad. If Kim Jung Un is unwilling to cease his obsession with nuclear weapons then we have an obligation to make it difficult for him to conduct business. This legislation makes it extremely clear to financial institutions: you can either do business with the United States of America or with North Korea but you cannot do business with both. This legislation passed the House this evening 415 to 2.

Today's #TBT takes us back to last Thursday when Indiana and the Indiana State Police welcomed 33 new troopers into the service of Hoosiers. Congratulations to the graduates of the 77th Recruit Academy.

Today, I introduced the Banning Lobbying And Safeguarding Trust (BLAST) Act. This is the most aggressive and stringent legislation of its kind currently in Congress. Hoosiers are tired of politicians putting their careers — present or future — ahead of the needs of their constituents. This bill is simple: you can never be a lobbyist after being a Representative or Senator. Congress must put Americans first, solve problems for Americans, and improve the lives of Americans.
